          Hi! Bloomberg is doing a survey of=C2=A0Money Stuff readers; plea=
se take a few minutes to fill it out if you haven=E2=80=99t yet. Thanks!

 =20
   =20
      My Forex Funds
   =20
 =20

Two stylized facts about the foreign exchange markets are:
=09It is very hard for retail traders to reliably make money trading curren=
cies, and=09They keep trying?

From first principles,=C2=A0it seems like a good idea to be on the other si=
de of their trades. If retail traders want to buy pounds, sell them pounds.=
 If they want to sell yen, buy yen from them. Etc.
If you do this as a full-time business, you=C2=A0will want to make some ref=
inements. Here are the three main refinements:
=09It can=E2=80=99t really be the case that retail investors lose money bec=
ause they consistently bet the wrong way on currency movements. (That would=
 take skill!) They lose money because (1) they make essentially random-chan=
ce bets on currency movements, with zero expected value, and (2) they lose =
a bit of money on each trade from commissions and spreads. So, if you are i=
n the business of trading with retail traders, make sure to charge them lot=
s of commissions and spreads.=09Meanwhile=C2=A0you=C2=A0don=E2=80=99t want =
to incur the costs of going out and buying yen, pounds, etc., each time you=
r retail customers do a trade. Ideally you will =E2=80=9Cbucket=E2=80=9D th=
eir trades: A customer comes to you and says =E2=80=9CI want to buy $1,000 =
worth of yen,=E2=80=9D they give you $1,000, and you say =E2=80=9Cokay grea=
t you have 14,400 yen in your account.=E2=80=9D
  [1]
 You don=E2=80=99t actually go and buy them any yen (you just make a note i=
n your books saying that you owe them 14,400 yen), and=C2=A0they don=E2=80=
=99t actually want yen (they just want to bet on the price). They will even=
tually close out the bet by selling you the 14,400 yen back for dollars, an=
d when they do you will cheerfully deliver them, like, $970. You keep their=
 $30 loss as your profit. No yen are ever involved.=09You will want them to=
 make=C2=A0leveraged=C2=A0bets: Instead of giving you $1,000 to buy $1,000 =
worth of yen, they=C2=A0give you, like, $100 to buy $10,000 worth of yen. T=
hen if the yen moves against them by 1%, they have lost all their money. If=
 the yen moves in their favor by 1% they have doubled their money, but the =
odds are in your favor.=C2=A0

The straightforward way to combine Refinements 2 and 3 is to trade FX=C2=A0=
futures, where the customers put down a small amount of collateral to enter=
 into a contract with you that pays out based on=C2=A0the price movements o=
f some currency pair, so (1) the trade is leveraged and (2) you never have =
to go out and actually buy any foreign currencies. FX futures are a very st=
andard way to trade currencies, so customers will be happy to trade them wi=
th you.
It should go without saying that none of these refinements are legal advice=
.
  [2]

You can make=C2=A0further, shadier=C2=A0refinements. For instance, if your =
customers are only trading with you =E2=80=94=C2=A0if you never go out and =
buy any actual currencies or do futures trades with outside dealers =E2=80=
=94=C2=A0you might think, well, it is not=C2=A0strictly=C2=A0necessary that=
 the prices I charge customers reflect actual market prices. They could jus=
t be=C2=A0different=C2=A0prices. If yen futures currently trade at 147.4 an=
d a customer comes to you looking to buy yen, you sell them yen at 146.9 to=
 the dollar. Why not, who cares, it=E2=80=99s all just happening on your ow=
n computer systems.=C2=A0You have to be careful with this: You probably hav=
e to show your customers some screen of bid and ask prices before they trad=
e, and if you show them that yen are 147.5 bid / 147.4 offered and they hit=
 =E2=80=9Cbuy,=E2=80=9D they might be puzzled to get only 146.9 yen for the=
ir dollar.
  [3]
=C2=A0But (1) they might not be (not everyone pays attention) and (2) you c=
an explain it away. =E2=80=9CAh, price impact, market slippage, the market =
was at 147.4 but then your big buy order moved it,=E2=80=9D you can say.
Another important set of refinements is: Some=C2=A0customers might actually=
 be good at trading foreign exchange, and will cost you money; what do you =
do about them? Your answer might be some combination of:
=09Shut down their accounts.=09Jack up the commissions, spreads, fake price=
s, etc., that you charge them, so that they start losing money.=09Stop buck=
eting their orders, route them to real markets, and let them trade with the=
ir own money with someone else; you charge commissions but no longer take t=
he other side of their bets.

The last important refinement, of course, is that you probably want to lie =
about all of this? =E2=80=9CWe charge zero commissions and all of our custo=
mers make money!=E2=80=9D might be a lie, but it is a better pitch than, li=
ke, =E2=80=9Cwe have found a maximally efficient way to fleece rubes like y=
ou.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0Everything else I said above can get you in trouble =E2=
=80=94=C2=A0none of it is legal advice! =E2=80=94=C2=A0but the lying is its=
 own=C2=A0separate way to get in trouble.
On Friday the US Commodity Futures Trading Commission brought a fun enforce=
ment action against Traders Global Group Inc., which runs an online FX trad=
ing platform called =E2=80=9CMy Forex Funds=E2=80=9D that =E2=80=9Coffers r=
etail customers the opportunity to become =E2=80=98professional traders,=E2=
=80=99=C2=A0using Traders Global=E2=80=99s money to trade against third-par=
ty =E2=80=98liquidity providers=E2=80=99=C2=A0and sharing in any trading pr=
ofits=E2=80=9D:
In return for the opportunity, customers pay certain fees to Traders Global=
, and are required by Traders Global to maintain a certain minimum amount o=
f account equity, referred to as a =E2=80=9Cdrawdown limit.=E2=80=9D Trader=
s Global assures customers that =E2=80=9Cyour success is our business,=E2=
=80=9D and =E2=80=9Cwe only make money when you do.=E2=80=9D Traders Global=
=E2=80=99s pitch has proven appealing to customers; more than 135,000 of th=
em signed up during the relevant period, paying at least $310 million in fe=
es.
But Traders Global is allegedly on the other side of all the trades:
Traders Global is a fraud. In reality, Traders Global is the counterparty t=
o substantially all customer trades. When customers make money, it means th=
at Traders Global loses money. =E2=80=A6=C2=A0Customers do not trade =E2=80=
=9Clive funds=E2=80=9D against =E2=80=9Cmultiple liquidity providers=E2=80=
=9D nor do customers share in =E2=80=9Ctrading profits,=E2=80=9D as Traders=
 Global claims. In reality, customers trade against Traders Global in an el=
ectronic trading environment that Traders Global controls.
The CFTC=E2=80=99s complaint hits all the highlights. There are commissions=
 of course:

Traders Global claims on its website that customer trades are subject to =
=E2=80=9Ccommissions=E2=80=9D of $3 per lot. Because Traders Global tells i=
ts customers that they are using Traders Global=E2=80=99s funds to trade, t=
he customer is led by Traders Global to believe that the commissions are th=
ose being charged to Traders Global by a liquidity provider, exchange, or o=
ther third party.
In fact, Traders Global is not charged commissions by any third party on =
=E2=80=9Ctrades=E2=80=9D for which it acts as counterparty. Traders Global =
fails to disclose, however, that it=E2=80=94not some third party=E2=80=94as=
sesses these commissions. The so-called =E2=80=9Ccommissions=E2=80=9D are s=
imply a charge against customer account equity imposed by Traders Global.

And customers make leveraged futures trades, maximizing their likelihood of=
 losing all their money and having to put in more:

A customer who signs up for an account is required to stay within a =E2=80=
=9Cdrawdown limit=E2=80=9D imposed by Traders Global. The drawdown limit re=
quires a customer to maintain a certain minimum amount of equity in his or =
her trading account. The amount varies with the size of account. =E2=80=A6
In a December 11, 2021, YouTube video, Kazmi explained that the drawdown is=
 designed =E2=80=9Cto force traders to get into that habit of locking in so=
me of the profits . . . .=E2=80=9D =E2=80=9CIf you lose all that money,=E2=
=80=9D Kazmi explained, =E2=80=9Cit=E2=80=99s not only you that=E2=80=99s l=
osing, it=E2=80=99s us as well right. Because we want to make you profitabl=
e so we can be profitable . . . .=E2=80=9D
If a customer exceeds the drawdown limit, Traders Global will =E2=80=9Cdisa=
ble=E2=80=9D (i.e., terminate) the customer=E2=80=99s account. If the custo=
mer wishes to continue with Traders Global, the customer is required to re-=
start their account and pay another fee.

=C2=A0
There is, uh, slippage:

Traders Global uses specialized software to automatically add =E2=80=9Cdela=
y=E2=80=9D or =E2=80=9Cslippage=E2=80=9D to customer orders. Traders Global=
 does this in order to reduce the likelihood, or amount, of a customer=E2=
=80=99s profitable trading=E2=80=A6.
By dialing the =E2=80=9Cslippage=E2=80=9D up, Traders Global sets the softw=
are to automatically execute a customer=E2=80=99s market order at a worse p=
rice than the best bid or offer displayed at the time the customer entered =
the order. For example, if a customer entered an order to buy a leveraged c=
ontract for Euros when the offer price displayed on the customer=E2=80=99s =
computer screen was $1.759, imposition of slippage would result in the orde=
r being executed at a higher price, e.g., $1.800.
Traders Global subjects most of its customers to some amount of delay or sl=
ippage.

And there is the handling of profitable traders, which involves dialing up =
the slippage:
Customers whose trading generates consistent profits, however, are subjecte=
d to longer delays and increased slippage, implemented by Traders Global.
And then, if that doesn=E2=80=99t work,=C2=A0routing them to other counterp=
arties so they are no longer Traders Global=E2=80=99s problem:

A very small number of customers trading =E2=80=9Clive=E2=80=9D accounts ma=
nage to trade profitably despite Traders Global=E2=80=99s attempts to handi=
cap them. After identifying such customers, Traders Global may route some o=
r all of these customers=E2=80=99 orders to an off-exchange leveraged forex=
 and commodities dealer outside the U.S. (hereinafter, the =E2=80=9CDealer=
=E2=80=9D). Traders Global refers to this as =E2=80=9CSTP=E2=80=99ing=E2=80=
=9D a customer=E2=80=99s account; =E2=80=9CSTP=E2=80=9D stands for =E2=80=
=9Cstraight-through processing.=E2=80=9D
STP=E2=80=99ing a customer is very rare. Of 24,000 customers with =E2=80=9C=
live=E2=80=9D accounts during the Relevant Period, fewer than 100 of them h=
ad a single trade STP=E2=80=99d.
In one respect, the STP=E2=80=99d customers get what they were promised=E2=
=80=94the opportunity to trade against a liquidity provider using Traders G=
lobal=E2=80=99s money, which Traders Global has on deposit with the Dealer,=
 in a margin account. =E2=80=A6
For customers on STP, Traders Global uses its specialized software to impos=
e an additional =E2=80=9Cspread=E2=80=9D on the price feed visible to STP=
=E2=80=99d customers. This spread results in a customer seeing=E2=80=94and =
believing himself or herself to be executed at=E2=80=94a worse price than w=
hat Traders Global got from the Dealer.

All the good stuff.=C2=A0I guess one=C2=A0question is how much of this is i=
llegal. The bones of it =E2=80=94=C2=A0=E2=80=9Cwe will trade futures clien=
ts with our customers, charge them commissions, close their contracts when =
their equity gets too low, and route orders we don=E2=80=99t want to other =
deals=E2=80=9D =E2=80=94=C2=A0seems kind of fine? As long as you don=E2=80=
=99t lie about it?
  [4]
