Grayscale Bitcoin Trust is a pot full of Bitcoins managed by an investment =
firm called Grayscale Investments LLC, part=C2=A0of Barry Silbert=E2=80=99s=
 Digital Currency Group.=C2=A0Shares of the trust trade publicly under the =
ticker GBTC, and you can buy them in your brokerage account. New shares can=
 be created by handing Grayscale a pile of=C2=A0Bitcoins and getting back n=
ew GBTC shares. For a long time a lot of people did this =E2=80=94=C2=A0it =
was called,   somewhat misleadingly, the =E2=80=9CGrayscale arbitrage=E2=80=
=9D =E2=80=94=C2=A0because GBTC traded at a big premium to the actual price=
 of Bitcoin, and so it now has about $16 billion worth of Bitcoin. But that=
 premium collapsed (in part because everyone kept doing the trade), and as =
of early last week=C2=A0GBTC traded at about a 25% discount to the value of=
 its pot of Bitcoins.
An odd feature of GBTC is that you can=E2=80=99t take the Bitcoins back=C2=
=A0out: You can create new shares by giving Grayscale Bitcoins, but you can=
=E2=80=99t get back the Bitcoins by handing back your shares. The pot can g=
row, but it can never shrink, so the discount persists.=C2=A0
If you read those two=C2=A0paragraphs and thought =E2=80=9Cwow=C2=A0I bet G=
rayscale charges a lot of money to manage that pot=E2=80=9D then congratula=
tions, you are qualified to work in financial services. Grayscale charges a=
 lot of money to manage that pot. GBTC investors complain about it, but wha=
t are they gonna do?=C2=A0They can=E2=80=99t take their money out! They can=
 sue =E2=80=94=C2=A0they have sued =E2=80=94=C2=A0but for the most part GBT=
C looks like a perpetual fee bonanza for Grayscale. It charges 2% per year,=
 on a pot of $16 billion, to just, like, hold onto the pot. Very lucrative.
Grayscale has bigger plans, though. Specifically it wants to convert GBTC i=
nto an exchange-traded fund. If GBTC were an ETF, then it is plausible=C2=
=A0that:
=09People would be able to take Bitcoins out.=C2=A0=09This would collapse t=
he discount, and GBTC would trade more or less in line with its net asset v=
alue.=09Therefore people wouldn=E2=80=99t take their Bitcoins out, but in f=
act would put more in, and the GBTC ETF would use its brand name and first-=
mover advantage to become even bigger. It would become the main way for ord=
inary investors to own Bitcoin.

Points 1 and 2 there seem like straightforward consequences of converting t=
o an ETF. Point 3 is more of a gamble. Maybe everyone will pile into a more=
 efficient Grayscale Bitcoin ETF. Maybe they won=E2=80=99t.
Grayscale wants to be an ETF, the US Securities and Exchange Commission kep=
t rejecting its applications for not very compelling reasons, Grayscale sue=
d and last week it won in court. It=E2=80=99s not an ETF yet, and things co=
uld go wrong, but they are trending in the right direction ETF-wise.
We  talked about the court case last week, and several readers=C2=A0emailed=
 me to ask: Did Grayscale=C2=A0want=C2=A0to win this case? The math is kind=
 of:
=09If GBTC is=C2=A0not=C2=A0an ETF, then it has a perpetually locked-up pot=
 of $16=C2=A0billion of Bitcoins, paying it 2% per year=C2=A0forever.=09If =
GBTC becomes an ETF, then (1) everyone can take their money out, (2)=C2=A0o=
ther=C2=A0Bitcoin ETFs will start to compete with it, (3) ETFs compete larg=
ely on fees and (4) come on, no other passive ETF charges anywhere close to=
 2%.

Grayscale winning this case kills its golden-goose fee stream. The optimal =
approach for Grayscale, a lot of people have long assumed, was to=C2=A0talk=
=C2=A0a lot about how aggressively it was fighting the SEC to become an ETF=
, in order to appease investors who want to collapse the discount, but to n=
ever actually win the case. If you win the case you lose the fees.
We have   talked about these incentives before. I think that this view is s=
omewhat too cynical, and that Grayscale probably expects to benefit by beco=
ming an ETF (by growing assets under management, by expanding into other re=
lated crypto-ETF-y businesses, by saving on legal fees) and wanted to win. =
(That=E2=80=99s why it did win!)=C2=A0But I take the point. Bloomberg=E2=80=
=99s Katie Greifeld and Vildana Hajric   reported last week:

Fresh off a pivotal win in court this week, Grayscale Investments LLC may s=
oon find itself in another fight: the $7.5 trillion US exchange-traded indu=
stry=E2=80=99s never-ending contest over fees. ...=C2=A0
The product carries a 2% fee in its current form. That compares to an avera=
ge of 0.54% across US-listed ETFs, and 1.48% for crypto exchange-traded pro=
ducts globally, Bloomberg Intelligence data show. =E2=80=A6 Asset-managemen=
t titans including BlackRock Inc., Invesco Ltd and Fidelity Investment =E2=
=80=94 known for their low-cost lineups =E2=80=94 all have similar applicat=
ions filed with the SEC, which the regulator is expected to respond to in t=
he coming days. Fees aren=E2=80=99t yet listed for their proposed products,=
 though history suggests it=E2=80=99ll be a fraction of what GBTC charges.
=E2=80=9CGrayscale is up against issuers such as BlackRock and Invesco who =
are highly accustomed to bludgeoning each other on fees,=E2=80=9D said Nate=
 Geraci, president of The ETF Store, an advisory firm. =E2=80=9CSpot-Bitcoi=
n ETFs will all generally look the same =E2=80=93 they simply hold Bitcoin =
=E2=80=94 which makes fees a key differentiator.=E2=80=9D
Grayscale=E2=80=99s Chief Executive Officer Michael Sonnenshein reiterated =
on Bloomberg Television Wednesday that the firm is =E2=80=9Ccommitted to lo=
wering fees when GBTC converts to an ETF,=E2=80=9D but declined to specify =
by how much.=C2=A0

GBTC had, for Grayscale, the extremely neat features of (1) being the only =
real publicly traded US Bitcoin product in a world where the SEC was blocki=
ng spot Bitcoin ETFs and (2)=C2=A0not allowing withdrawals. A GBTC ETF will=
 have neither of those advantages.

