d merger situation at Sculptor Capital Management Inc., the publicly traded=
 hedge fund firm.=C2=A0Sculptor=E2=80=99s board has agreed to sell the comp=
any for $11.15 per share to Rithm Capital Corp., which would keep Jimmy Lev=
in, Sculptor=E2=80=99s chief executive officer and chief investment officer=
, around to run Sculptor=E2=80=99s funds. But since the Rithm deal was anno=
unced in July, a group of hedge fund managers including Boaz Weinstein, Bil=
l Ackman and Marc Lasry has offered to buy the company themselves=C2=A0for =
$12.25 per share, which they later raised to $12.76. Sculptor=E2=80=99s boa=
rd has said no, arguing that the Weinstein offer, while obviously=C2=A0high=
er=C2=A0than Rithm=E2=80=99s, is less certain. In particular, either deal w=
ould be contingent on most of Sculptor=E2=80=99s clients approving the new =
