ed and lawyered way? There are apparently impediments.
Last Thursday, Sculptor=E2=80=99s former CEO Rob Shafir =E2=80=94=C2=A0who =
ran the firm for a while between its founder Dan Och and its current CEO Le=
vin =E2=80=94=C2=A0 sent the board an open letter supporting Weinstein:
Your fiduciary duties require you to maximize value for Sculptor's sharehol=
ders. $12.76 with committed financing is clearly superior to $11.15. It is =
not credible that Bidder J =E2=80=93 publicly reported to be comprised of l=
eading investors such as Boaz Weinstein, Jeff Yass, Bill Ackman and Marc La=
sry =E2=80=93 would not be acceptable to limited partners, especially at th=
e 50.1% threshold publicly reported as compared to the 85% in the deal with=
 Rithm Capital Corp. ("Rithm"). It is also not credible to maintain the pos=
ition that this group does not have the funds and resources to complete thi=
s transaction. I therefore will not be supporting your proposed sale to Rit=
hm.
Shafir presumably knows Sculptor=E2=80=99s business and clients better than=
, you know, I do, and he thinks that at least 50.1% of them would be happy =
with Weinstein and friends. Still seems like best practices to ask them but=
 what do I know.
Another open question is: What happens next? Sculptor=E2=80=99s stock was t=
rading at about $11.75 as of noon today, and it has been above the $11.15 R=
ithm deal price for the last two weeks or so. Sculptor has a contract to se=
ll itself to Rithm, contingent on a vote of Sculptor=E2=80=99s shareholders=
, and as far as the board is concerned I guess it is moving ahead with that=
 vote. There is no date set yet for the vote, but there is a  preliminary=
=C2=A0proxy statement, and the board has consistently said that it has no r=
eason to engage with Weinstein and that the Rithm deal is still on.
But if Sculptor does hold the vote, will it win? Will the Rithm deal go thr=
ough? Levin and a few other current Sculptor executives  have agreed to vot=
e their shares in favor of the deal, and  they own about a quarter of the v=
otes, but the rest are up for grabs, and Och and Shafir, who own about 16% =
