10px;">
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;"><em>Hi! Bloomberg is doing a survey of=C2=A0<a=
 href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/32613823.263427/aHR0=
cHM6Ly9ibWVkaWEuaWFkMS5xdWFsdHJpY3MuY29tL2pmZS9mb3JtL1NWXzhCbVBONEFCdVlvYWN=
Ycw/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBe8283abf" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"=
itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none=
 !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border=
-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">Money Stuff readers</a>; ple=
ase take a few minutes to fill it out if you haven=E2=80=99t yet. Thanks!</=
em></p>
<table class=3D"header" width=3D"100%" border=3D"0" cellspacing=3D"0" cellp=
adding=3D"0">
<tr>
<td class=3D"body-header-container" style=3D"border-collapse: collapse; mso=
-table-lspace: 0pt; mso-table-rspace: 0pt;">
<h2 style=3D"font-weight: bold; font-family: &quot;Arial Black&quot;, Arial=
, Helvetica, sans-serif; letter-spacing: -1px; font-size: 20px; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; margin: 0px; padding: 16px 0px =
5px;">My Forex Funds</h2>
</td>
</tr>
</table>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Two stylized facts about the foreign exchange =
markets are:</p>
<ul style=3D"list-style-type: disc; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;">=
=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">It is very hard for retail traders to =
reliably make money trading currencies, and</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bott=
om: 5px;">They keep trying?</li>
</ul>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">From first principles,=C2=A0it seems like a go=
od idea to be on the other side of their trades. If retail traders want to =
buy pounds, sell them pounds. If they want to sell yen, buy yen from them. =
Etc.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">If you do this as a full-time business, you=C2=
=A0will want to make some refinements. Here are the three main refinements:=
</p>
<ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;"=
>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">It can=E2=80=99t really be the case t=
hat retail investors lose money because they consistently bet the wrong way=
 on currency movements. (That would take skill!) They lose money because (1=
) they make essentially random-chance bets on currency movements, with zero=
 expected value, and (2) they lose a bit of money on each trade from commis=
sions and spreads. So, if you are in the business of trading with retail tr=
aders, make sure to charge them lots of commissions and spreads.</li>=09<li=
 style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Meanwhile=C2=A0<em>you=C2=A0</em>don=E2=80=
=99t want to incur the costs of going out and buying yen, pounds, etc., eac=
h time your retail customers do a trade. Ideally you will =E2=80=9C<a href=
=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/32613823.263427/aHR0cHM6L=
y9lbi53aWtpcGVkaWEub3JnL3dpa2kvQnVja2V0X3Nob3BfKHN0b2NrX21hcmtldCk/607f07ce=
ef4b8524a319a23cBee7849cc" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" t=
arget=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important;=
 border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-styl=
e: solid; background-color: #ccc;">bucket</a>=E2=80=9D their trades: A cust=
omer comes to you and says =E2=80=9CI want to buy $1,000 worth of yen,=E2=
=80=9D they give you $1,000, and you say =E2=80=9Cokay great you have 14,40=
0 yen in your account.=E2=80=9D<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnot=
e-1" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !imp=
ortant; background-color: transparent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[1]</span>
</a> You don=E2=80=99t actually go and buy them any yen (you just make a no=
te in your books saying that you owe them 14,400 yen), and=C2=A0they don=E2=
=80=99t actually want yen (they just want to bet on the price). They will e=
ventually close out the bet by selling you the 14,400 yen back for dollars,=
 and when they do you will cheerfully deliver them, like, $970. You keep th=
eir $30 loss as your profit. No yen are ever involved.</li>=09<li style=3D"=
margin-bottom: 5px;">You will want them to make=C2=A0<em>leveraged=C2=A0</e=
m>bets: Instead of giving you $1,000 to buy $1,000 worth of yen, they=C2=A0=
give you, like, $100 to buy $10,000 worth of yen. Then if the yen moves aga=
inst them by 1%, they have lost all their money. If the yen moves in their =
favor by 1% they have doubled their money, but the odds are in your favor.=
=C2=A0</li>
</ol>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The straightforward way to combine Refinements=
 2 and 3 is to trade FX=C2=A0<em>futures</em>, where the customers put down=
 a small amount of collateral to enter into a contract with you that pays o=
ut based on=C2=A0the price movements of some currency pair, so (1) the trad=
e is leveraged and (2) you never have to go out and actually buy any foreig=
n currencies. FX futures are a very standard way to trade currencies, so cu=
stomers will be happy to trade them with you.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">It should go without saying that none of these=
 refinements are legal advice.<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote=
-2" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-botto=
m-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !impo=
rtant; background-color: transparent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[2]</span>
</a></p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">You can make=C2=A0further, shadier=C2=A0refine=
ments. For instance, if your customers are only trading with you =E2=80=94=
=C2=A0if you never go out and buy any actual currencies or do futures trade=
s with outside dealers =E2=80=94=C2=A0you might think, well, it is not=C2=
=A0<em>strictly=C2=A0</em>necessary that the prices I charge customers refl=
ect actual market prices. They could just be=C2=A0<em>different=C2=A0</em>p=
rices. If yen futures currently trade at 147.4 and a customer comes to you =
looking to buy yen, you sell them yen at 146.9 to the dollar. Why not, who =
cares, it=E2=80=99s all just happening on your own computer systems.=C2=A0Y=
ou have to be careful with this: You probably have to show your customers s=
ome screen of bid and ask prices before they trade, and if you show them th=
at yen are 147.5 bid / 147.4 offered and they hit =E2=80=9Cbuy,=E2=80=9D th=
ey might be puzzled to get only 146.9 yen for their dollar.<a class=3D"foot=
note-index" href=3D"#footnote-3" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: =
none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; bo=
rder-bottom-style: none !important; background-color: transparent !importan=
t; display: inline-block;">
<span>[3]</span>
</a>=C2=A0But (1) they might not be (not everyone pays attention) and (2) y=
ou can explain it away. =E2=80=9CAh, price impact, market slippage, the mar=
ket was at 147.4 but then your big buy order moved it,=E2=80=9D you can say=
.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Another important set of refinements is: <em>S=
ome=C2=A0</em>customers might actually be good at trading foreign exchange,=
 and will cost you money; what do you do about them? Your answer might be s=
ome combination of:</p>
<ul style=3D"list-style-type: disc; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;">=
=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Shut down their accounts.</li>=09<li s=
tyle=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Jack up the commissions, spreads, fake prices,=
 etc., that you charge them, so that they start losing money.</li>=09<li st=
yle=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Stop bucketing their orders, route them to real=
 markets, and let them trade with their own money with someone else; you ch=
arge commissions but no longer take the other side of their bets.</li>
</ul>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The last important refinement, of course, is t=
hat you probably want to lie about all of this? =E2=80=9CWe charge zero com=
missions and all of our customers make money!=E2=80=9D might be a lie, but =
it is a better pitch than, like, =E2=80=9Cwe have found a maximally efficie=
nt way to fleece rubes like you.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0Everything else I said above=
 can get you in trouble =E2=80=94=C2=A0none of it is legal advice! =E2=80=
=94=C2=A0but the lying is its own=C2=A0separate way to get in trouble.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">On Friday the US Commodity Futures Trading Com=
mission <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/32613823.2=
63427/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuY2Z0Yy5nb3YvUHJlc3NSb29tL1ByZXNzUmVsZWFzZXMvODc3MS0yM=
w/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB29c92934" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"it=
emscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !=
important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-b=
ottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">brought a fun enforcement acti=
on</a> against Traders Global Group Inc., which runs an online FX trading p=
latform called =E2=80=9CMy Forex Funds=E2=80=9D that =E2=80=9Coffers retail=
 customers the opportunity to become =E2=80=98professional traders,=E2=80=
=99=C2=A0using Traders Global=E2=80=99s money to trade against third-party =
=E2=80=98liquidity providers=E2=80=99=C2=A0and sharing in any trading profi=
ts=E2=80=9D:</p>
<blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In return for the opportunity, cus=
tomers pay certain fees to Traders Global, and are required by Traders Glob=
al to maintain a certain minimum amount of account equity, referred to as a=
 =E2=80=9Cdrawdown limit.=E2=80=9D Traders Global assures customers that =
=E2=80=9Cyour success is our business,=E2=80=9D and =E2=80=9Cwe only make m=
oney when you do.=E2=80=9D Traders Global=E2=80=99s pitch has proven appeal=
ing to customers; more than 135,000 of them signed up during the relevant p=
eriod, paying at least $310 million in fees.</p></blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But Traders Global is allegedly on the other s=
ide of all the trades:</p>
<blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Traders Global is a fraud. In real=
ity, Traders Global is the counterparty to substantially all customer trade=
s. When customers make money, it means that Traders Global loses money. =E2=
=80=A6=C2=A0Customers do not trade =E2=80=9Clive funds=E2=80=9D against =E2=
=80=9Cmultiple liquidity providers=E2=80=9D nor do customers share in =E2=
=80=9Ctrading profits,=E2=80=9D as Traders Global claims. In reality, custo=
mers trade against Traders Global in an electronic trading environment that=
 Traders Global controls.</p></blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The CFTC=E2=80=99s <a href=3D"https://link.mai=
l.bloombergbusiness.com/click/32613823.263427/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuY2Z0Yy5nb3Yvb=
WVkaWEvOTE5Ni9lbmZ0cmFkZXJzZ2xvYmFsZ3JvdXBjb21wbGFpbnQwODI5MjMvZG93bmxvYWQ/=
607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB98f3eaae" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"item=
scope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !im=
portant; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bot=
tom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">complaint</a> hits all the highl=
ights. There are commissions of course:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Traders Global claims on its website that cust=
omer trades are subject to =E2=80=9Ccommissions=E2=80=9D of $3 per lot. Bec=
ause Traders Global tells its customers that they are using Traders Global=
=E2=80=99s funds to trade, the customer is led by Traders Global to believe=
 that the commissions are those being charged to Traders Global by a liquid=
ity provider, exchange, or other third party.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In fact, Traders Global is not charged commiss=
ions by any third party on =E2=80=9Ctrades=E2=80=9D for which it acts as co=
unterparty. Traders Global fails to disclose, however, that it=E2=80=94not =
some third party=E2=80=94assesses these commissions. The so-called =E2=80=
=9Ccommissions=E2=80=9D are simply a charge against customer account equity=
 imposed by Traders Global.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">And customers make leveraged futures trades, m=
aximizing their likelihood of losing all their money and having to put in m=
ore:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">A customer who signs up for an account is requ=
ired to stay within a =E2=80=9Cdrawdown limit=E2=80=9D imposed by Traders G=
lobal. The drawdown limit requires a customer to maintain a certain minimum=
 amount of equity in his or her trading account. The amount varies with the=
 size of account. =E2=80=A6</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In a December 11, 2021, YouTube video, Kazmi e=
xplained that the drawdown is designed =E2=80=9Cto force traders to get int=
o that habit of locking in some of the profits . . . .=E2=80=9D =E2=80=9CIf=
 you lose all that money,=E2=80=9D Kazmi explained, =E2=80=9Cit=E2=80=99s n=
ot only you that=E2=80=99s losing, it=E2=80=99s us as well right. Because w=
e want to make you profitable so we can be profitable . . . .=E2=80=9D</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">If a customer exceeds the drawdown limit, Trad=
ers Global will =E2=80=9Cdisable=E2=80=9D (i.e., terminate) the customer=E2=
=80=99s account. If the customer wishes to continue with Traders Global, th=
e customer is required to re-start their account and pay another fee.</p>
</blockquote>
<blockquote>=C2=A0</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">There is, uh, slippage:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Traders Global uses specialized software to au=
tomatically add =E2=80=9Cdelay=E2=80=9D or =E2=80=9Cslippage=E2=80=9D to cu=
stomer orders. Traders Global does this in order to reduce the likelihood, =
or amount, of a customer=E2=80=99s profitable trading=E2=80=A6.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">By dialing the =E2=80=9Cslippage=E2=80=9D up, =
Traders Global sets the software to automatically execute a customer=E2=80=
=99s market order at a worse price than the best bid or offer displayed at =
the time the customer entered the order. For example, if a customer entered=
 an order to buy a leveraged contract for Euros when the offer price displa=
yed on the customer=E2=80=99s computer screen was $1.759, imposition of sli=
ppage would result in the order being executed at a higher price, e.g., $1.=
800.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Traders Global subjects most of its customers =
to some amount of delay or slippage.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">And there is the handling of profitable trader=
s, which involves dialing up the slippage:</p>
<blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Customers whose trading generates =
consistent profits, however, are subjected to longer delays and increased s=
lippage, implemented by Traders Global.</p></blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">And then, if that doesn=E2=80=99t work,=C2=A0r=
outing them to other counterparties so they are no longer Traders Global=E2=
=80=99s problem:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">A very small number of customers trading =E2=
=80=9Clive=E2=80=9D accounts manage to trade profitably despite Traders Glo=
bal=E2=80=99s attempts to handicap them. After identifying such customers, =
Traders Global may route some or all of these customers=E2=80=99 orders to =
an off-exchange leveraged forex and commodities dealer outside the U.S. (he=
reinafter, the =E2=80=9CDealer=E2=80=9D). Traders Global refers to this as =
=E2=80=9CSTP=E2=80=99ing=E2=80=9D a customer=E2=80=99s account; =E2=80=9CST=
P=E2=80=9D stands for =E2=80=9Cstraight-through processing.=E2=80=9D</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">STP=E2=80=99ing a customer is very rare. Of 24=
,000 customers with =E2=80=9Clive=E2=80=9D accounts during the Relevant Per=
iod, fewer than 100 of them had a single trade STP=E2=80=99d.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In one respect, the STP=E2=80=99d customers ge=
t what they were promised=E2=80=94the opportunity to trade against a liquid=
ity provider using Traders Global=E2=80=99s money, which Traders Global has=
 on deposit with the Dealer, in a margin account. =E2=80=A6</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">For customers on STP, Traders Global uses its =
specialized software to impose an additional =E2=80=9Cspread=E2=80=9D on th=
e price feed visible to STP=E2=80=99d customers. This spread results in a c=
ustomer seeing=E2=80=94and believing himself or herself to be executed at=
=E2=80=94a worse price than what Traders Global got from the Dealer.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">All the good stuff.=C2=A0I guess one=C2=A0ques=
tion is how much of this is illegal. The bones of it =E2=80=94=C2=A0=E2=80=
=9Cwe will trade futures clients with our customers, charge them commission=
s, close their contracts when their equity gets too low, and route orders w=
e don=E2=80=99t want to other deals=E2=80=9D =E2=80=94=C2=A0seems kind of f=
ine? As long as you don=E2=80=99t lie about it?<a class=3D"footnote-index" =
href=3D"#footnote-4" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !import=
ant; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-=
style: none !important; background-color: transparent !important; display: =
inline-block;">
<span>[4]</span>
</a>=C2=A0But the combination, plus the alleged lying, is quite lucrative:<=
/p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">[Chief Executive Officer Murtuza] Kazmi has us=
ed the proceeds from the Traders Global fraud to fund a luxury lifestyle.</=
p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In April 2022, Kazmi paid $1.6 million to purc=
hase a Lamborghini Aventador at auction. In December 2022, Kazmi paid $3.3 =
million for a Bugatti racecar.</p>
</blockquote>
