<h2 style=3D"font-weight: bold; font-family: &quot;Arial Black&quot;, Arial=
, Helvetica, sans-serif; letter-spacing: -1px; font-size: 20px; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; margin: 0px; padding: 16px 0px =
5px;">Grayscale fees</h2>
</td>
</tr>
</table>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Grayscale Bitcoin Trust is a pot full of Bitco=
ins managed by an investment firm called Grayscale Investments LLC, part=C2=
=A0of Barry Silbert=E2=80=99s Digital Currency Group.=C2=A0Shares of the tr=
ust trade publicly under the ticker GBTC, and you can buy them in your brok=
erage account. New shares can be created by handing Grayscale a pile of=C2=
=A0Bitcoins and getting back new GBTC shares. For a long time a lot of peop=
le did this =E2=80=94=C2=A0it was called, <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloo=
mbergbusiness.com/click/32613823.263427/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9=
vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjItMTItMDUvY3J5cHRvLWhhZC1hLWNyZWRpdC1idWJibGU_Y2=
1waWQ9QkJEMDkwNTIzX01PTkVZU1RVRkYmdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc291cmNlPW5ld=
3NsZXR0ZXImdXRtX3Rlcm09MjMwOTA1JnV0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1tb25leXN0dWZm/607f07ceef4=
b8524a319a23cB3e695c03" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" targ=
et=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; bo=
rder-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: =
solid; background-color: #ccc;">  somewhat misleadingly</a>, the =E2=80=9CG=
rayscale arbitrage=E2=80=9D =E2=80=94=C2=A0because GBTC traded at a big pre=
mium to the actual price of Bitcoin, and so it now has about $16 billion wo=
rth of Bitcoin. But that premium collapsed (in part because everyone kept d=
oing the trade), and as of early last week=C2=A0GBTC traded at about a 25% =
discount to the value of its pot of Bitcoins.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">An odd feature of GBTC is that you can=E2=80=
=99t take the Bitcoins back=C2=A0<em>out: </em>You can create new shares by=
 giving Grayscale Bitcoins, but you can=E2=80=99t get back the Bitcoins by =
handing back your shares. The pot can grow, but it can never shrink, so the=
 discount persists.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">If you read those two=C2=A0paragraphs and thou=
ght =E2=80=9Cwow=C2=A0I bet Grayscale charges a lot of money to manage that=
 pot=E2=80=9D then congratulations, you are qualified to work in financial =
services. Grayscale charges a lot of money to manage that pot. GBTC investo=
rs complain about it, but what are they gonna do?=C2=A0<em>They can=E2=80=
=99t take their money out! </em>They can sue =E2=80=94=C2=A0<a href=3D"http=
s://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/32613823.263427/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuY=
mxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjMtMDMtMDcvZnR4LXdhbnRzLWl0cy1i=
aXRjb2lucy1iYWNrLWZyb20tZ3JheXNjYWxlP2NtcGlkPUJCRDA5MDUyM19NT05FWVNUVUZGJnV=
0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWwmdXRtX3NvdXJjZT1uZXdzbGV0dGVyJnV0bV90ZXJtPTIzMDkwNSZ1dG=
1fY2FtcGFpZ249bW9uZXlzdHVmZg/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB4efefabe" itemprop=3D=
"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #0000=
00; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bott=
om-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">the=
y have sued</a> =E2=80=94=C2=A0but for the most part GBTC looks like a perp=
etual fee bonanza for Grayscale. It charges 2% per year, on a pot of $16 bi=
llion, to just, like, hold onto the pot. Very lucrative.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Grayscale has bigger plans, though. Specifical=
ly it wants to convert GBTC into an exchange-traded fund. If GBTC were an E=
TF, then it is plausible=C2=A0that:</p>
<ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;"=
>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">People would be able to take Bitcoins=
 out.=C2=A0</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">This would collapse th=
e discount, and GBTC would trade more or less in line with its net asset va=
lue.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Therefore people <em>wouldn=
=E2=80=99t</em> take their Bitcoins out, but in fact would put more in, and=
 the GBTC ETF would use its brand name and first-mover advantage to become =
even bigger. It would become the main way for ordinary investors to own Bit=
coin.</li>
</ol>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Points 1 and 2 there seem like straightforward=
 consequences of converting to an ETF. Point 3 is more of a gamble. Maybe e=
veryone will pile into a more efficient Grayscale Bitcoin ETF. Maybe they w=
on=E2=80=99t.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Grayscale wants to be an ETF, the US Securitie=
s and Exchange Commission kept rejecting its applications for not very comp=
elling reasons, Grayscale sued and last week it won in court. It=E2=80=99s =
not an ETF yet, and things could go wrong, but they are trending in the rig=
ht direction ETF-wise.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">We <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusin=
ess.com/click/32613823.263427/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL=
2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjMtMDgtMjkvZ3JheXNjYWxlLWNhbi1iZS1hLWJpdGNvaW4tZXRmP2NtcGlk=
PUJCRDA5MDUyM19NT05FWVNUVUZGJnV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWwmdXRtX3NvdXJjZT1uZXdzbGV=
0dGVyJnV0bV90ZXJtPTIzMDkwNSZ1dG1fY2FtcGFpZ249bW9uZXlzdHVmZg/607f07ceef4b852=
4a319a23cBa2b1c947" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=
=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; bord=
er-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: so=
lid; background-color: #ccc;"> talked about</a> the court case last week, a=
nd several readers=C2=A0emailed me to ask: Did Grayscale=C2=A0<em>want=C2=
=A0</em>to win this case? The math is kind of:</p>
<ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;"=
>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">If GBTC is=C2=A0<em>not=C2=A0</em>an =
ETF, then it has a perpetually locked-up pot of $16=C2=A0billion of Bitcoin=
s, paying it 2% per year=C2=A0forever.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5=
px;">If GBTC becomes an ETF, then (1) everyone can take their money out, (2=
)=C2=A0<em>other=C2=A0</em>Bitcoin ETFs will start to compete with it, (3) =
ETFs compete largely on fees and (4) come on, no other passive ETF charges =
anywhere close to 2%.</li>
</ol>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Grayscale winning this case kills its golden-g=
oose fee stream. The optimal approach for Grayscale, a lot of people have l=
ong assumed, was to=C2=A0<em>talk=C2=A0</em>a lot about how aggressively it=
 was fighting the SEC to become an ETF, in order to appease investors who w=
ant to collapse the discount, but to never actually win the case. If you wi=
n the case you lose the fees.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">We have <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloomberg=
business.com/click/32613823.263427/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGlu=
aW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjMtMDMtMDcvZnR4LXdhbnRzLWl0cy1iaXRjb2lucy1iYWNrLWZyb20=
tZ3JheXNjYWxlP2NtcGlkPUJCRDA5MDUyM19NT05FWVNUVUZGJnV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWwmdX=
RtX3NvdXJjZT1uZXdzbGV0dGVyJnV0bV90ZXJtPTIzMDkwNSZ1dG1fY2FtcGFpZ249bW9uZXlzd=
HVmZg/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cC4efefabe" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=
=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: =
none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; bo=
rder-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">  talked about</a> these=
 incentives before. I think that this view is somewhat too cynical, and tha=
t Grayscale probably expects to benefit by becoming an ETF (by growing asse=
ts under management, by expanding into other related crypto-ETF-y businesse=
s, by saving on legal fees) and wanted to win. (That=E2=80=99s why it did w=
in!)=C2=A0But I take the point. Bloomberg=E2=80=99s Katie Greifeld and Vild=
ana Hajric <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/3261382=
3.263427/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9uZXdzL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjMtMDgtMz=
EvZ3JheXNjYWxlLWdidGMtZmFjZXMtZmVlLXdhci13aXRoLWJsYWNrcm9jay1pbi1iaXRjb2luL=
WJ0Yy1ldGYtcmFjZT9jbXBpZD1CQkQwOTA1MjNfTU9ORVlTVFVGRiZ1dG1fbWVkaXVtPWVtYWls=
JnV0bV9zb3VyY2U9bmV3c2xldHRlciZ1dG1fdGVybT0yMzA5MDUmdXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPW1vbmV=
5c3R1ZmY/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB8c4ccf18" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscop=
e=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration:=
 none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; b=
order-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">  reported last week</a=
>:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Fresh off a pivotal win in court this week, Gr=
ayscale Investments LLC may soon find itself in another fight: the $7.5 tri=
llion US exchange-traded industry=E2=80=99s never-ending contest over fees.=
 ...=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The product carries a 2% fee in its current fo=
rm. That compares to an average of 0.54% across US-listed ETFs, and 1.48% f=
or crypto exchange-traded products globally, Bloomberg Intelligence data sh=
ow. =E2=80=A6 Asset-management titans including BlackRock Inc., Invesco Ltd=
 and Fidelity Investment =E2=80=94 known for their low-cost lineups =E2=80=
=94 all have similar applications filed with the SEC, which the regulator i=
s expected to respond to in the coming days. Fees aren=E2=80=99t yet listed=
 for their proposed products, though history suggests it=E2=80=99ll be a fr=
action of what GBTC charges.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=E2=80=9CGrayscale is up against issuers such =
as BlackRock and Invesco who are highly accustomed to bludgeoning each othe=
r on fees,=E2=80=9D said Nate Geraci, president of The ETF Store, an adviso=
ry firm. =E2=80=9CSpot-Bitcoin ETFs will all generally look the same =E2=80=
=93 they simply hold Bitcoin =E2=80=94 which makes fees a key differentiato=
r.=E2=80=9D</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Grayscale=E2=80=99s Chief Executive Officer Mi=
chael Sonnenshein reiterated on Bloomberg Television Wednesday that the fir=
m is =E2=80=9Ccommitted to lowering fees when GBTC converts to an ETF,=E2=
=80=9D but declined to specify by how much.=C2=A0</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">GBTC had, for Grayscale, the extremely neat fe=
atures of (1) being the only real publicly traded US Bitcoin product in a w=
orld where the SEC was blocking spot Bitcoin ETFs and (2)=C2=A0<em>not allo=
wing withdrawals</em>. A GBTC ETF will have neither of those advantages.</p=
>
